.TH DHCP 8
.SH NAME
dhcp \- DHCP client configuration for ktcp
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "dhcp"
.RB [ yes
.IR | no ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B DHCP
is a built-in subsystem of the ktcp TCP/IP daemon.
When enabled, ktcp automatically negotiates an IP address, netmask, and default
gateway using the DHCP protocol at startup.
.PP
DHCP is configured in
.BR /etc/eth0.cfg .
If the first line of this file is
.BR dhcp ,
the DHCP client is started before any static configuration is applied.
The static IP, netmask, and gateway values in the same file are ignored while
DHCP is active.
.SH STATE MACHINE
The client follows the standard DHCP exchange:
.PP
.RS
.nf
DISCOVER \(-> OFFER \(-> REQUEST \(-> ACK \(-> BOUND
.fi
.RE
.PP
1. Sends a broadcast DISCOVER on UDP port 67.
.br
2. Receives OFFER from a DHCP server.
.br
3. Sends a REQUEST for the offered address.
.br
4. Receives ACK and applies the lease (IP, netmask, gateway).
.PP
If a NAK is received at any stage, the client restarts from DISCOVER with a new
transaction ID.
.SH RETRY
Exponential backoff is used for retries:
.IP \(bu 2
Initial timeout: 4 ticks
.IP \(bu 2
Doubles each retry, capped at 16 ticks
.IP \(bu 2
After 5 failed retries, restarts from INIT
.PP
Once the address is bound, the retry timer is disabled.
.SH OPTIONS REQUESTED
The client requests the following DHCP options:
.IP \(bu 2
Subnet mask (option 1)
.IP \(bu 2
Router / default gateway (option 3)
.IP \(bu 2
DNS server (option 6)
.IP \(bu 2
Lease time (option 51)
.SH "UDP IMPLEMENTATION"
DHCP uses the UDP layer built into ktcp.
UDP provides a lightweight, connectionless transport on top of IP.
Unlike TCP, there is no handshake or reliable delivery; packets are sent
and received directly.
.SS Sending
A UDP send constructs an 8-byte header (source port, destination port,
length, zeroed checksum) and passes the packet to the IP layer.
The IP layer adds its header and hands the packet to the appropriate
network driver (Ethernet or SLIP).
.SS Receiving
When an incoming IP packet has protocol 0x11 (UDP), the IP layer calls
.BR udp_process (),
which looks up the destination port in a table of registered sockets.
Each registered socket has a callback function; when a matching port is
found, the callback is invoked with the IP header, source port, and
payload data.
If no socket is registered for the destination port, an ICMP
port-unreachable message is sent back.
.SS Registration
A subsystem (like DHCP) registers a port and callback via
.BR udp_register ()
before sending any packets.
This reserves one of the 4 available UDP socket slots
.RB ( MAX_UDP_SOCKS ).
The DHCP client registers port 68 and receives all replies in its
.BR dhcp_input ()
callback.
.SS Packet Flow
.RS
.nf
Send:  dhcp_send_discover\(\)
         \(-> udp_send(255.255.255.255, 67, 68, buf, len, 0)
               \(-> ip_sendpacket() \(-> Ethernet driver

Recv:  Ethernet driver
         \(-> ip_recvpacket()
               \(-> udp_process()
                     \(-> udp_socks[i].callback\(\)  = dhcp_input\(\)
.fi
.RE
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /etc/eth0.cfg
Contains the
.B dhcp
keyword on the first line to enable the client.
.SH EXAMPLE
To enable DHCP, create
.B /etc/eth0.cfg
with:
.PP
.RS
.nf
dhcp
.fi
.RE
.PP
Then start the network:
.PP
.RS
.nf
/etc/rc.d/rc.net
.fi
.RE
.SH NOTES
DHCP is only available when the kernel is compiled with
.BR "CONFIG_DHCP=y" .
.PP
Only one DHCP client can run per interface.
The client uses UDP port 68 and does not renew the lease before expiry.
.PP
When DHCP is active, static configuration from
.B /etc/eth0.cfg
(IP, netmask, gateway) is skipped.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR netconf (8),
.BR ifconfig (8),
.BR ktcp (8).
